		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Wow, you got a really great find here. Thanks tepples.
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The game is for an "open" platform, or it is for one that has been suitably cracked and is no longer supported by the console maker. These include Linux, Windows, Mac OS X, Pocket PC, NES, Mega Drive/Genesis, Dreamcast, and Game Boy Advance. </div>
<br />Well, I guess the GBA is still supported by Nintendo, and <em>Final Fantasy VI Advance</em> was released less than two years ago in Europe and close to two years ago in Japan.
<br />However, there is no doubt that the Game Boy and Game Boy Color should be added on the list, and probably the Super NES too (even if it may not have been as much reverse engineered ?).
<br />
<br />And I belive the ESRB is the standard in United States. As Bunnyboy stated, it's not compulsory, which was really a surprise to me. Usually I reconise import games by their rating logo, if it's PEGI I know it's an european game and if it's ESRB I know it's from the US. If I can't make sense of the pictograms on the box, likely it's form japan  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=":wink:" title="Wink" />

		

