	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Japan uses <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_Entertainment_Rating_Organization" class="postlink">CERO</a>.
<br />
<br />The "TM" doesn't require any sort of registration. It just gives you a stronger claim in a <a href="http://www.uspto.gov/web/offices/tac/tmfaq.htm#Search005" class="postlink">common law trademark</a>, which in the United States is mostly state law. Registration generally happens after the first use of a mark, so you'll often see things change from TM to ® in later editions of a product after registration. Compare Animal Crossing for GameCube (used TM) to Animal Crossing: Wild World for DS (used ®).
<br />
<br /><strong>GBC: Definitely dead, an ex-parrot.</strong>
<br />Nintendo no longer sells significant quantities of hardware capable of playing GBC games. Wikipedia's article about the GBA SP, the last system capable of playing GBC games, states that sales in North America stopped abruptly after the third quarter of 2007, suggesting that it was probably discontinued in favor of the DS Lite for the Christmas season. GBA SP sales continue in "Other" regions though, but just barely: only about 80,000 in the entire third quarter of 2008.
<br />
<br /><strong>GBA: Probably dead.</strong>
<br />In the past 11 months, the warez scene has released only 10 GBA roms, and the most recent scene release of a commercial game (#2809 according to PH) was in mid-April 2008. At this rate, I'd guess the original commercial era of GBA is over. Consider it dead once the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nintendo_DSi" class="postlink">DSi</a> is out worldwide in the second quarter of this year, as DSi doesn't play GBA games or even DS games that use a SLOT-2 controller.
<br />
<br /><strong>Super NES: Not cracked.</strong>
<br />I seem to remember from the CIC reverse engineering topic that the Super NES CIC uses the same microcontroller architecture as the one in the NES, but the program is entirely different and not yet analyzed. So we're limited to prying CICs from original games or using a Super 3D Noah's Ark-style lock-on cart.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


